{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 
{Perhaps White didn't notice the pawn was defended and will now resign?} 5. d4 
{[%cal Bd4d5,Be4e5][%csl Rf6,Re5,Gd4,Ge4] Alas, no, and we now find ourselves in 
a strange, dark, twisted realm where up is down, left is right, and madness 
shall reign lest we follow a narrow, perilous path of chess righteousness. Or... 
well, OK, for the less valiant and somewhat more lazy among us, there is another 
way, namely to give back the piece at a judicious moment in return for an 
excellent position. There are many ways to do this, but the following method is 
considered one of Black's both simplest and best approaches.} Nc6 (5... Ng6 
{will be covered in later lines.}) 6. d5 Bb4 {[%cal Bf6e4,Gb4e1][%csl Rc3]} 
({For the much braver/foolhardy} 6... Ne5 {, see the 'Dark Alley Defense'.}) 7. 
dxc6 Nxe4 {[%csl Rc3,Rc6] Exploiting not only the pin on White's Knight but also 
the fact that the pawn on c6 can't capture without rapidly mobilizing Black's 
development.} 8. Qd4 Qe7 $15 {[%cal Ge7b4,Ge7e4] While White is perhaps closer 
to equality here than someone who hangs a Knight on move four should really be, 
Black nevertheless enjoys a strong initiative and the satisfaction of being the 
hunter and not the hunted.} *

