{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 
{Perhaps White didn't notice the pawn was defended and will now resign?} 5. d4 
Nc6 ({For the more practical} 5... Ng6 {, see the next two variations.}) 6. d5 
Ne5 ({For the less ambitious/bonkers} 6... Bb4 {, see the previous line.}) {The 
6... Ne5 variation, while objectively straight up winning for Black, is also, as 
we shall see, a questionable practical choice for any mortal defender.} 7. f4 
Ng6 8. e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gd5,Rf6] The position has begun to resemble some sort of 
left-handed Alekhine's Defense gone horribly wrong.} Ng8 9. d6 {[%csl Rc7,Rf8] A 
key move for white, after which we are temporarily unable to develop any of our 
minor pieces.} cxd6 10. exd6 Qf6 $13 ({So as to remove the pawn on d6 but also, 
somewhat alarmingly, to allow our King to flee to d8. After} Qf6 11. Nb5 {White 
defends d6 and menaces Nc7+, and while after} 11... Nxf4 {Black can create a 
theoretically winning counterattack, I can't really recommend this line as it is 
simply too long and messy to remember.}) *

