{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 5. d4 
{As we saw in the last variation, a computer assuring you you're 'safe' is akin 
to thinking that because the bad guy in a scary movie just got tossed off a 
cliff that he's no longer going to be much of a bother. Therefore Black's more 
customary line of defense follows a different, slightly less chaotic path.} Ng6 
{Instead of jumping to c6 and then back to e5 (after d5), and then to g6 (after 
f4), Black chooses to cut to the chase and put his persecuted steed on g6 
immediately.} 6. e5 Ng8 ({After} Ng8 7. Bc4 {we arrive at a critical position 
for the entire opening. White threatens 8. Qf3 and imminent disaster. Black has 
a number of defenses, but for the purposes of this guide, we will look at two: 
the 'Euwe Defense' and what I recommended instead, the 'Greed is Good 
Defense'.}) 7. Bc4 {First let's examine the Euwe Defense, named after the only 
World Champion who has bothered to comment at all on this opening. However, as 
we shall see, Euwe's 'refutation' leads to positions that are far from entirely 
clear and, perhaps even more importantly, precisely what White expects us to 
blithely wander into.} d5 {[%cal Bc7c6,Bc8e6] Giving up second pawn to simplify 
the defense.} 8. Bxd5 c6 9. Bb3 (9. Be4 {is also possible, after which Black 
should probably try} 9... f5 10. Bf3 Nh4 {.}) Be6 {[%cal Bd8d7,Be8c8] Black's 
plan is to play ...Qd7, ...O-O-O, and possibly ...c5. White, however, can 
maintain his pawn center via the following maneuver.} 10. O-O Qd7 11. Ne4 O-O-O 
12. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5] Securing the center. Note that we're loath to 
exchange light-squared bishops as not only would the White f-pawn (f4,f5, etc.) 
be harder to restrain, but the open a-file after axb3 could also prove irksome.} 
Be7 13. f4 Nh6 {[%cal Bh6f5] Now that f4 has been played, we can finally 
'develop' our Knight to h6 (which otherwise might have run into Bxh6).} 14. Qe2 
{White's imposing pawn center prevents us from generating much play with our 
pieces.} Rhe8 {[%cal Bf7f5]} ({Preparing ...f5, which currently fails to 15. 
exf6 and mayhem on the e-file.}) 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. b4 $13 {While Black is still 
'better', it must be admitted that: • A) This is a fairly long variation with 
lots of other tries for White along the way, and • B) Even here White 
maintains two strong central pawns and an enduring initiative as reasonable 
'human' compensation for the piece. Therefore, instead of this, I recommend the 
'Greed is Good Defense', which we will examine in the next few lessons.} *

