{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 5. d4 
{As we saw in the last variation, a computer assuring you you're 'safe' is akin 
to thinking that because the bad guy in a scary movie just got tossed off a 
cliff that he's no longer going to be much of a bother. Therefore Black's more 
customary line of defense follows a different, slightly less chaotic path.} Ng6 
{Instead of jumping to c6 and then back to e5 (after d5), and then to g6 (after 
f4), Black chooses to cut to the chase and put his persecuted steed on g6 
immediately.} 6. e5 Ng8 ({After} Ng8 7. Bc4 {we arrive at a critical position 
for the entire opening. White threatens 8. Qf3 and imminent disaster. Black has 
a number of defenses, but for the purposes of this guide, we will look at two: 
the 'Euwe Defense' and what I recommended instead, the 'Greed is Good 
Defense'.}) 7. Bc4 {In the previous variation (the 'Euwe Defense') we saw that 
7... d5 doesn't completely solve all of Black's problems, at least on a 
practical level. Now we look at the lesser known but both easier to play and 
objectively better 'Greed is Good' variation!} c6 {[%cal Bd7d5,Gc6d5] This at 
first passive looking move is actually the simplest way to deal with White's 
initiative.} 8. Qf3 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gf3f7][%csl Rf7] Seemingly strong, but Black 
has a good and thematic reply.} d5 {[%csl Rc4,Gd5]} 9. exd6 Be6 {[%cal 
Gf8d6,Gd8d6][%csl Rd6] The difference between this and the Euwe Defense becomes 
clear: White has been forced to part with his powerful pawn on e5. Here it will 
inevitably be captured on d6 after which we can straightforwardly complete our 
development.} 10. d5 ({White's best try to make something of his rapidly 
evaporating initiative, and not one to take lightly - if now} 10. d5 10... cxd5 
11. Bb5+ {is absolutely crushing.}) Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f3][%csl Rc4,Rf3] While 
I'm not sure how well this works against demons or the undead, in chess the best 
way to deal with bullies is to stand up to them! After this fork, Black's 
troubles disappear in the cold, fresh morning air of reason. The next two 
variations each feature a futile attempt to swindle Black from this position - 
11. Qh5 and 11. Qe2.} *

