[Comment "surviving-the-halloween-gambit/course/28925, variation/5050147"]

{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 5. d4 
{As we saw in the last variation, a computer assuring you you're 'safe' is akin 
to thinking that because the bad guy in a scary movie just got tossed off a 
cliff that he's no longer going to be much of a bother. Therefore Black's more 
customary line of defense follows a different, slightly less chaotic path.} Ng6 
{Instead of jumping to c6 and then back to e5 (after d5), and then to g6 (after 
f4), Black chooses to cut to the chase and put his persecuted steed on g6 
immediately.} 6. e5 Ng8 ({After} Ng8 7. Bc4 {we arrive at a critical position 
for the entire opening. White threatens 8. Qf3 and imminent disaster. Black has 
a number of defenses, but for the purposes of this guide, we will look at two: 
the 'Euwe Defense' and what I recommended instead, the 'Greed is Good 
Defense'.}) 7. Bc4 {In the previous variation (the 'Euwe Defense') we saw that 
7... d5 doesn't completely solve all of Black's problems, at least on a 
practical level. Now we look at the lesser known but both easier to play and 
objectively better 'Greed is Good' variation!} c6 {This at first passive looking 
move is actually the simplest way to deal with White's initiative.} 8. Qf3 
{Seemingly strong, but Black has a good and thematic reply.} d5 9. exd6 Be6 {The 
difference between this and the Euwe Defense becomes clear: White has been 
forced to part with his powerful pawn on e5. Here it will inevitably be captured 
on d6 after which we can straightforwardly complete our development.} 10. d5 Ne5 
{Here we examine the first of two possible ways White can attempt to trick Black 
after 10...Ne5.} 11. Qh5 {[%cal Gh5e5,Gd5e6][%csl Re6,Re5] This scary looking 
attempt is easily parried provided we remain calm and not run upstairs to the 
attic where your uncle Fester told you never to play in, especially on cold, 
rainy nights during thunderstorms while eerie music softly plays in the 
background.} Nxc4 12. dxe6 Nxd6 {[%cal Gd6f7][%csl Gf7] Remembering that Knights 
can move backwards is often the key to a successful defense.} 13. Ne4 {[%cal 
Be4d6,Gh5f7,Ge6f7][%csl Rf7] More tricks!} g6 ({We must continue to remain calm 
and not play something silly like} 13... Nf6 $2 14. Nxd6+ Qxd6 15. Qxf7+ Kd8 16. 
Bg5 $1) 14. exf7+ Nxf7 ({If} Nxf7 15. Qf3 {here, simply} 15... Qd5 $1 {followed 
by 16... O-O-O, seems pretty good due to, well, being a piece up and all.}) 15. 
Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e8,Be4f6][%csl Re8] Not White's subtlest threat.} ({Amazingly 
enough we can actually play} 15. Qe2 15... Bg7 $5 {here, but I'm going to 
recommend something slightly less bonkers.}) Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e2]} 16. Bd2 {[%cal 
Bd2c3,Gc3h8][%csl Rh8] Threatening 17. Bc3.} Bg7 {[%cal Gg7b2]} 17. O-O-O O-O-O 
{Almost out of the woods, though as any scary film aficionado knows, that's when 
you should be at your most vigilant...} 18. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3a7][%csl Ra7]} 
({Hitting a7 and intending 19. Re1 followed by some sort of something somewhere. 
Of course we can defend now with} 18. Qe3 18... Kb8 {and end this variation 
right here, but what's the fun in that when we can instead mock our provocateur 
with once last dance with the devil...}) Nf6 {[%cal Be7e4][%csl Re4] Intending 
immediate simplification, but White now embarks upon one last bloody rampage.} 
19. Qxa7 Nxe4 {No Fear!} 20. Qa8+ Kd7 21. Qxb7+ ({if instead} 21. Bg5+ {,} 21... 
Ke6 $3 {and White is, amazingly enough, completely out of tricks.}) Ke8 22. 
Qxe7+ ({Alternatively,} 22. Qxc6+ Kf8 {and Black is up two pieces with a strong 
Queenside attack to boot.}) Kxe7 23. Rhe1 Nd6 {Once again Nd6 saves the day!} 
24. f3 {Regaining one piece but at the cost of whatever remained of White's 
initiative.} Kf7 25. fxe4 Nc4 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gc4b2][%csl Rb2,Rd2] White is now 
technically materially equal, but also completely lost due to the awkward Bishop 
on d2 and vulnerable queenside.} 26. Bc3 Bxc3 27. bxc3 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Ke6 $19 
{And the rest is pretty simple. This variation is admittedly quite long but also 
very straightforward, but if you want something even simpler there's 18... Kb8 
after 18. Qe3. Next up is White's other way to attempting to confuse the issue 
after 10....Ne5.} *

