{Welcome to one of the most fearsome openings - the dreaded Halloween Gambit! A 
gambit so vile that no Grandmaster has yet dared to try it by the light of a 
serious OTB event, but make no mistake - in the depths of the internet it has 
been known to snare many an unwary denizen. So let's begin - if you dare!} 1. e4 
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 {Suspecting nothing...} 4. Nxe5 {Gasp! Clearly our 
opponent is a complete lunatic. Or possibly Simon Williams. Or both!} Nxe5 5. d4 
{As we saw in the last variation, a computer assuring you you're 'safe' is akin 
to thinking that because the bad guy in a scary movie just got tossed off a 
cliff that he's no longer going to be much of a bother. Therefore Black's more 
customary line of defense follows a different, slightly less chaotic path.} Ng6 
{Instead of jumping to c6 and then back to e5 (after d5), and then to g6 (after 
f4), Black chooses to cut to the chase and put his persecuted steed on g6 
immediately.} 6. e5 Ng8 ({After} Ng8 7. Bc4 {we arrive at a critical position 
for the entire opening. White threatens 8. Qf3 and imminent disaster. Black has 
a number of defenses, but for the purposes of this guide, we will look at two: 
the 'Euwe Defense' and what I recommended instead, the 'Greed is Good 
Defense'.}) 7. Bc4 {In the 'Euwe Defense' variation we saw that 7... d5 doesn't 
completely solve all of Black's problems, at least on a practical level. Now we 
look at the lesser known but both easier to play and objectively better 'Greed 
is Good' variation!} c6 {This at first passive looking move is actually the 
simplest way to deal with White's initiative.} 8. Qf3 {Seemingly strong, but 
Black has a good and thematic reply.} d5 9. exd6 Be6 {The difference between 
this and the Euwe Defense becomes clear: White has been forced to part with his 
powerful pawn on e5. Here it will inevitably be captured on d6 after which we 
can straightforwardly complete our development.} 10. d5 Ne5 {Finally we come to 
White's last, and best, attempt to try and make our life a living hell. However, 
with a few judicious maneuvers we can overcome our brutish adversary and triumph 
in a blaze of reasonableness.} 11. Qe2 Nxc4 12. dxe6 {[%cal Ge2c4][%csl 
Gd6,Ge6,Rc4] Those pawns do look scary.} Nxd6 {[%cal Gd6f7]} 13. Bf4 ({Much more 
cunning than just} 13. exf7+ Kxf7 {after which we can simply develop our 
kingside and, if neccesary, castle 'by hand'.}) Qf6 {[%cal Gf6f4,Be8c8][%csl 
Rf4]} ({The most incisive defense - other moves would lead to unnecessary 
quantities of murk - for instance,} 13... Qe7 $2 14. O-O-O $1 O-O-O 15. Rhe1 $1 
fxe6 ({or} 15... Qxe6 16. Qd2 $1) 16. Qe3 $1 Kb8 17. Qxe6 Qxe6 18. Rxe6 {and we 
lose our pinned Knight on d6.}) 14. exf7+ Kxf7 {As we have seen before, there's 
worse places for our King than f7. White now must struggle to create 
counterplay.} 15. Be5 ({At this point we are faced with a pragmatic choice:} 15. 
Be5 15... Qe6 {and let White develop a very small initiative -} 16. O-O-O Nf6 
17. Rhe1 Nc4 18. f4 {etc. - that will be defused with accurate defense, or 
immediately sacrifice the exchange to enter a much better two minor pieces vs. 
rook endgame. For the sake of simplicity I'm going with the latter, but it 
should be pointed out that the former is probably the objectively more accurate 
approach.}) Re8 {[%cal Be8e2][%csl Re5,Re2,Re1] After this move, we have 
officially reached the end of nonsense.} 16. Bxf6 Rxe2+ 17. Nxe2 Nxf6 $17 {This 
endgame is significantly better for Black, probably winning. Suffice it to say 
that if this was what White wanted out of the Halloween Attack, then they're 
much crazier than we thought! This concludes our survey on the Halloween Attack. 
Hopefully it has provided you with the means to never again be victimized by the 
twisted practitioners of this vile, unnatural mockery of the noble game of 
chess. On the other hand, if you are one of the twisted practitioners, check out 
my other series, 'Torment Your Foes with the Halloween Attack (as White)', 
coming soon to a Chessable near you. Happy Halloween, - NM John Chernoff} *

